28
00:01:55,629 --> 00:01:57,117
Scott: Let's talk about computer

29
00:01:57,137 --> 00:01:57,378
Scott: mice.".

30
00:01:57,680 --> 00:02:03,379
Rym: See, Scott and I differ on mice in one way, though we also agree on another thing very much, and I'm just gonna get this straight out.

31
00:02:03,760 --> 00:02:07,100
Scott: Okay, well first of all, mice that are not USB suck.

32
00:02:07,580 --> 00:02:07,826
Scott: Yeah.

33
00:02:07,846 --> 00:02:10,348
Scott: Second of all, mice that are not optical suck.

34
00:02:10,610 --> 00:02:18,233
Rym: Third, tracked balls are awesome for very specific things like Rampart, or if you have carpal tunnel, they otherwise suck.

35
00:02:18,476 --> 00:02:18,739
Scott: Yes.

36
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:23,211
Scott: People who talk about tracked balls like they're so much better, it's like, "Whatever, dude.

37
00:02:23,393 --> 00:02:23,676
Scott: You got a

38
00:02:23,697 --> 00:02:24,000
Scott: problem.".

39
00:02:25,301 --> 00:02:26,636
Rym: They're not as bad as those Dvorak people.

40
00:02:26,656 --> 00:02:26,858
Rym: Yes.

41
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:31,665
Scott: Tablets are okay as a pointing device, but they're not mice, so they don't count.

42
00:02:32,369 --> 00:02:42,540
Rym: Now, the real big thing I want to get out there is that you pretty much should be using your mouse at the highest sensitivity you can bear, because one, that'll prevent carpal tunnel as far as I can see, because you're not moving your wrist hardly at all.

43
00:02:43,201 --> 00:02:48,779
Rym: I mean, I flick my fingers, just my fingers, a half an inch, and I can cover my entire screen pretty much.

44
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:49,260
Scott: Yes.

45
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:58,860
Scott: Mouse sensitivity is basically if the mouse says I moved an inch, then that moves the arrow on the screen a certain distance on the monitor.

46
00:02:59,500 --> 00:03:11,580
Scott: If you have low sensitivity, then moving the mouse an inch will move the arrow on the screen an inch, which means you have to pick up the mouse and move the mouse around a whole lot in order to move the arrow on the screen around a whole lot.

47
00:03:11,720 --> 00:03:17,540
Rym: Also, if you got to move it slowly like that, you're going to be turning your wrist and twisting your wrist and moving your wrist.

48
00:03:17,860 --> 00:03:19,460
Scott: And you're going to be using your whole arm to move that.

49
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:21,600
Rym: You shouldn't be moving your wrist when you're using a mouse.

50
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:22,980
Rym: You're going to hurt yourself if you keep doing that.

51
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:25,620
Scott: If you turn your sensitivity way, way up, right?

52
00:03:26,140 --> 00:03:26,382
Scott: Sure.

53
00:03:26,463 --> 00:03:32,058
Scott: At first, it might feel like the mouse is out of control, because you move it even a little bit and the arrow flies all over the place.

54
00:03:32,118 --> 00:03:32,540
Scott: out of control.

55
00:03:32,640 --> 00:03:33,935
Scott: You can't aim at anything, but...

56
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:36,000
Rym: Increase it gradually and you'll get used to it.

57
00:03:36,180 --> 00:03:42,519
Scott: If you practice with it, you can just use your thumb and your pinky to move the mouse in millimeters.

58
00:03:42,882 --> 00:03:46,120
Rym: And yet you still have the fine control due to things like acceleration.

59
00:03:46,600 --> 00:03:51,340
Scott: Yes, you have precision control over the arrow on the screen while barely moving your hand at all.

60
00:03:51,921 --> 00:03:53,959
Scott: And that's the way I say it should be.

61
00:03:54,120 --> 00:03:54,979
Scott: And you should learn to do that.

62
00:03:55,581 --> 00:03:56,980
Rym: But anyway, we're not going to talk about that.

63
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:58,800
Rym: You don't need a lecture from us on that topic.

64
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:00,459
Rym: You need a lecture from us on a bunch of other topics.

65
00:04:02,322 --> 00:04:06,120
Rym: So there's only one kind of mouse that I will use and I can't stand any other mouse.

66
00:04:06,420 --> 00:04:09,460
Rym: Mice have to be the standard mouse size or smaller.

67
00:04:10,022 --> 00:04:12,340
Rym: And they got to have two buttons and a scroll wheel in the middle.

68
00:04:12,726 --> 00:04:13,579
Rym: And nothing else.

69
00:04:14,901 --> 00:04:20,260
Scott: I need a mouse with more buttons and I need a mouse with wireless.

70
00:04:20,839 --> 00:04:24,560
Scott: And I need a mouse with the fanciness and the comfort of the hand.

71
00:04:24,820 --> 00:04:26,600
Rym: See, the problem is a lot of cheaper wireless mice.

72
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:28,240
Rym: There's a tiny delay that just bothers me.

73
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:29,660
Scott: That's a cheap wireless mouse.

74
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:33,520
Scott: You got to get a high quality wireless mouse or it's not worth it.

75
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:36,316
Rym: See, now I don't mind the thumb button so much or even the pinky button, but...

76
00:04:37,102 --> 00:04:38,119
Scott: The pinky button is no good.

77
00:04:38,641 --> 00:04:46,340
Rym: I think the real problem for me is that any mouse that has all these things, it's like all modern fancy mice have this big hump in them, especially the wireless mice.

78
00:04:46,460 --> 00:04:47,398
Rym: They stick the batteries in there.

79
00:04:48,282 --> 00:04:51,000
Rym: And I don't like the palm of my hand to touch my mouse.

80
00:04:51,120 --> 00:04:51,878
Rym: It really bothers me.

81
00:04:52,283 --> 00:04:53,260
Scott: Oh, I don't know why it bothers you.

82
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:54,120
Scott: I like the mouse.

83
00:04:54,140 --> 00:05:01,340
Rym: I touch my mouse at any given time with all my fingers, like the tips of all my fingers and no other part of my body ever touches the mouse.

84
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:05,060
Scott: See, I like the mouse to feel like a glove on the bottom of my hand.

85
00:05:05,180 --> 00:05:07,120
Scott: Like if they made a mouse like finger grooves.

86
00:05:07,665 --> 00:05:08,338
Scott: No, that's bad.

87
00:05:08,520 --> 00:05:14,360
Rym: Because if the mouse is touching the palm of your hand, you cannot prevent yourself from moving your wrist back and forth at least a little.

88
00:05:15,060 --> 00:05:15,457
Scott: Yeah, I can.

89
00:05:16,048 --> 00:05:16,198
Rym: How?

90
00:05:17,503 --> 00:05:18,719
Scott: It just slides on my hand.

91
00:05:20,164 --> 00:05:20,878
Rym: I'm not seeing it.

92
00:05:21,723 --> 00:05:22,719
Scott: I don't know what your problem is.

93
00:05:22,961 --> 00:05:23,240
Rym: I don't know.

94
00:05:23,320 --> 00:05:24,280
Rym: I think you use mice weird.

95
00:05:24,802 --> 00:05:25,220
Scott: I mean, I don't know.

96
00:05:25,240 --> 00:05:26,180
Scott: I think you use mice weird.

97
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:28,900
Rym: I use mice in the most possible, awesome way you could use them.

98
00:05:28,900 --> 00:05:29,174
Scott: No, no.

99
00:05:29,520 --> 00:05:35,080
Scott: But anyway, I have the Logitech MX1000 and I think it's a pretty awesome mouse.

100
00:05:35,661 --> 00:05:40,120
Rym: I have these... Well, there used to be back in the day, there were like two Logitech mice that were optical.

